NL Opt 3: Multivariate Optimization and Regression Analysis¶

Packages Used: Functions from the following packages are used below.

  • DataFrames
  • Optim
  • Plots
  • Statistics
  • XLSX

1. Multivariate Optimization¶

Multivariate optimization corresponds to the optimization of a function of two or more variables, and is the most flexible type of nonlinear optimization.

$ \begin{eqnarray} \mathbf{x}^* &=& \mathrm{arg}\underset{x}{\operatorname{min}} \bigl\{ f(\mathbf{x}) \bigr\} \\ T\!C^* &=& f(\mathbf{x}^*) \end{eqnarray}$

Ex 1: Euclidean 2-D distances¶

Given a 2-D point x and m other 2-D points in P, create a function fdist2 to determine the Euclidean (i.e., straight-line) distance d from x to each of the m points in P:

$ \begin{array}{l} \quad\bf{x} = \left[ \begin{array}{cc} x_1 & x_2 \end{array} \right],\quad \bf{P} = \left[ \begin{array}{cc} p_{1,1} & p_{1,2} \\ \vdots & \vdots \\ p_{m,1} & p_{m,2} \end{array} \right] \\ \quad\bf{d} = \left[ \begin{array}{cc} d_1 \\ \vdots \\ d_m \end{array} \right] = \left[ \begin{array}{c} \sqrt{\left(x_1 - p_{1,1}\right)^2 + \left(x_2 - p_{1,2}\right)^2} \\ \vdots \\ \sqrt{\left(x_1 - p_{m,1}\right)^2 + \left(x_2 - p_{m,2}\right)^2} \end{array} \right] \end{array} $

The best way to start is to create some example data for which you know the correct answer:

In [1]:
x = [3. 1.]                 # Note: x = 1 x 2 row vector, not 2-element array
                            # (also, values are real valued, not integer) 
P = [1. 1.; 6. 1.; 6. 5.];

Note: In this example the orientaton of x is important. x = 1 2 row vector is a 2-D point, while x = 2 1 as a column vector would be interpreted as two 1-D points. In Julia, can use x = [3. 1.] to create x as a row vector, instead of x = [3., 1.] with a comma between values that would create a 2-element array, which would be then interpreted as a 2 1 column vector.

In the figure, the sum of the distances from x to the three points in P is 10:

The first step is to subtract x from each row in P:

In [2]:
x .- P
Out[2]:
32 Matrix{Float64}:
  2.0   0.0
 -3.0   0.0
 -3.0  -4.0

Square each element of the result:

In [3]:
(x .- P).^2
Out[3]:
32 Matrix{Float64}:
 4.0   0.0
 9.0   0.0
 9.0  16.0

Add the elements in each row:

In [4]:
sum((x .- P).^2, dims = 2)
Out[4]:
31 Matrix{Float64}:
  4.0
  9.0
 25.0

Then take the square root and assign the result to d:

In [5]:
d = sqrt.(sum((x .- P).^2, dims = 2))
Out[5]:
31 Matrix{Float64}:
 2.0
 3.0
 5.0

A function can be created and then called to assign the result to d:

In [6]:
fdist2(x,P) = sqrt.(sum((x .- P).^2, dims = 2))
d = fdist2(x,P)
Out[6]:
31 Matrix{Float64}:
 2.0
 3.0
 5.0

As it is written, the function will work for points of any dimension, not just 2-D points. For n-dimensional points, x would be an 1 n row vector and P an m n matrix; e.g., for 4-D points:

In [7]:
@show [x x]
@show [P P]
d = fdist2([x x],[P P])

[x x] = [3.0 1.0 3.0 1.0]
[P P] = [1.0 1.0 1.0 1.0; 6.0 1.0 6.0 1.0; 6.0 5.0 6.0 5.0]
Out[7]:
31 Matrix{Float64}:
 2.8284271247461903
 4.242640687119285
 7.0710678118654755

To determine the number of elements in an array:

In [8]:
@show length(x)
@show length(P);

length(x) = 2
length(P) = 6

To determine the dimensions of an array:

In [9]:
@show size(P)
@show size(P,1)
@show size(P,2);

size(P) = (3, 2)
size(P, 1) = 3
size(P, 2) = 2

The function fdist2 can now be used inside of any expression; e.g., to calculate the sum of the distances from x to the points in P:

In [10]:
sum(fdist2(x,P))
Out[10]:
10.0

Ex 2: Minimum-distance location¶

The function optimize performs general-purpose multivariate optimization. Instead of specifying a bounded range, as was done for univariate optimization using optimize, for multivariate optimization, an initial location x0 is specified, from which the function determines the location x that minimizes the sum of distances to each point in P:

In [11]:
using Optim
x0 = [0. 0.]    
optimize(x -> sum(fdist2(x,P)), x0)
Out[11]:
 * Status: success

 * Candidate solution
    Final objective value:     8.697184e+00

 * Found with
    Algorithm:     Nelder-Mead

 * Convergence measures
    ((y-y))/n  1.0e-08

 * Work counters
    Seconds run:   0  (vs limit Inf)
    Iterations:    45
    f(x) calls:    89

To assign the optimal location and minimum total distance values to variables:

In [12]:
res = optimize(x -> sum(fdist2(x,P)), x0)
x = res.minimizer
sumd = res.minimum
@show x sumd;

x = [5.089389040930581 1.9663250607367784]
sumd = 8.697184389632483

To return only the optimal location:

In [13]:
x = optimize(x -> sum(fdist2(x,P)), x0).minimizer
Out[13]:
12 Matrix{Float64}:
 5.08939  1.96633

Nelder-Mead method¶

The Nelder-Mead method is the most widely used procedure for unconstrained multivariate optimization (more details on Julia's Optim package implementation of Nelder-Mead). The reason for its popularity is that is the most efficient direct, or gradient-free, method available, in contrast to gradient-based methods that require gradients to be either provided or estimated, which can be difficult or impossible for some functions.

It uses a d + 1 simplex to move towards an optimal solution. In 2-D, the simplex is a triangle and, as different simplexes are created through reflection, expansion, etc. (see figure, below), it looks an amoeba moving; as a result, Nelder-Mead is sometimes referred to as the "amoeba method" (animation of Nelder-Mead).

In [14]:
using Plots
scatter(P[:,1],P[:,2], legend=false)
Out[14]:
In [15]:
function fdist2_with_plot_x(x,P)
    scatter!([x[1]],[x[2]], markersize=1)
    return sqrt.(sum((x .- P).^2, dims = 2))
end
x0 = [0. 0.]
x = optimize(x -> sum(fdist2_with_plot_x(x,P)), x0).minimizer
scatter!([x[1]],[x[2]], markersize=4, markercolor=:red)
Out[15]:

2. Regression¶

Ex 3: Periodic Vaccine Fulfillment Operations (continued from the last meeting)¶

Continuing with this example, assume that the amount ordered by the customer is available at the beginning of each week prior to having to make the size decision. Once fulfillment begins, additional demand can occur during the week, and some orders are canceled; as a result, the final demand at the end of week will differ from the amount ordered at the start of the week. Never the less, it is thought that using each week's orders to help determine each week's container size decision can increase total profit.

In [16]:
using Plots
d = [237, 214, 161, 146, 331, 159, 423, 332, 139, 327, 152, 98, 116]
o = [121, 143, 63, 80, 198, 52, 160, 162, 85, 106, 129, 141, 106]
display(plot([o d], xlabel="Week", ylabel="Units", xticks=1:length(d), label=["Orders" "Demand"]))
scatter(o, d, legend=false, xlabel="Orders", ylabel="Demand", label="(o, d)")
Out[16]:

The correlation of the two time series can be calculated to see how likely the order data may help in estimating demand:

In [17]:
using Statistics
cor(o,d)
Out[17]:
0.5994685344117657

Linear Regression¶

Almost 60% correlation is promising, worth including the order data in the analysis. This can be done through linear regression by making demand a function of order data. Different objective functions can be used to fit the model. Will first consider a sqared-error (L2) loss function:

L2 loss¶

In [18]:
using Optim
fd(,o) = [1] .+ [2]o
fL2() = sum((fd(,o) .- d).^2)
2 = optimize( -> fL2(), [0. 1.]).minimizer    # Starting 2 values = [0., 1.]
Out[18]:
12 Matrix{Float64}:
 44.8644  1.45651

The starting values for the intercept and slope parameters for the Nelder-Mead procedure are $\alpha2 = \left[ 0., 1. \right]$. Here it is placed inside the call to Optimize; previously, in Ex 2: Minimum-distance location, the starting point to a variable x0 and then used inside the call to Optimize.

In [19]:
plot!(o -> fd(2,o),0,maximum(o), label="L2")
Out[19]:

L1 loss function¶

In [20]:
fL1() = sum(abs.(fd(,o) .- d))
1 = optimize( -> fL1(), [0. 1.]).minimizer
display(plot!(o -> fd(1,o),0,maximum(o), label="L1", legend=true))
1
Out[20]:
12 Matrix{Float64}:
 81.6667  1.25926

Maximizing Profit using Regression¶

In our previous meeting, profit was maximized using just the prior demand data. The following table summarizes the results fromt the last meeting:

Procedure Total Profit
UB 11,340
Previous week's demand 6996
Mean of prior demand (L2) 8542
Median of prior demand (L1) 7592
Max total profit using demand 9407

Can think of the demand estimates used previously as single parameter estimation models. Linear regression can be used to provide two parameter estimation models.

In [21]:
p = 5                                    # Unit price
c = 1                                    # Unit cost
f(q,di) = p*minimum([q, di]) - c*q;     # Profit

The total profit function needs to change since a different size ($q_i$) is associated with each different demand ($d_i$). In the single-parameter models considered previousely, the same size ($q$) was associated with each different demand ($d_i$).

In [22]:
f(q,d) = sum([f(q[i],d[i]) for i in 1:length(d)]);    # Total profit

Just using the order data as the demand estimate:

In [23]:
f(o,d)
Out[23]:
5969

L2 linear regression using orders:

In [24]:
f(fd(2,o),d)
Out[24]:
9326.541799581575

L1 linear regression using orders:

In [25]:
f(fd(1,o),d)
Out[25]:
9602.259258268658

Linear regression using orders and profit maximization as objective:

In [26]:
 = optimize( -> -f(fd(,o),d), [0. 1.]).minimizer
display(plot!(o -> fd(,o),0,maximum(o), label="", legend=:topleft))
, f(fd(,o),d)
Out[26]:
([77.21818171600432 1.5727272746809993], 9853.636363517973)

How would week 14's size be determined¶

In [27]:
o14 = Int(round(mean(o)))
q14 = fd(,o14)
o14, q14
Out[27]:
(119, 264.3727274030432)

Quadratic regression¶

In [28]:
fd(,o) = [1] .+ [2]o .+ [3]o.^2
Q = optimize( -> -f(fd(,o),d), [0. 1. 0.]).minimizer
display(plot!(o -> fd(Q,o),0,maximum(o), label="Q", legend=:topleft))
Q, f(fd(Q,o),d)
Out[28]:
([-0.07401761718654201 3.5362280660091927 -0.009175237352469189], 9856.37058432405)

Multivariate regression¶

Assume hospital admissions data is available at the beginnning of each week. See if that can help:

In [29]:
a = [1690, 1715, 1557, 1717, 1818, 1803, 1702, 1639, 1500, 1654, 1495, 1509, 1659]
display(scatter(a, d, legend=false, xlabel="Admissions", ylabel="Demand", label=false))
cor(a,d), f(a,d)
Out[29]:
(0.4409008999338393, -7283)

Around a 44% correlation indicates a moderate relationship that may help. Using just admissions to estimate demand gave a negative total profit; since the magnitude of the admission values differs from the demand values, there is no reason to expect without normalization that this would not be the case.

In order to effectively use the admissions data, it can be added to the model along with the order data in a multivaraiate regression:

In [30]:
fd(,o,a) = [1] .+ [2]o .+ [3]a
MV = optimize( -> -f(fd(,o,a),d), [0. 1. 1.]).minimizer
f(fd(MV,o,a),d)
Out[30]:
9879.975131342047
